    "value": "Here is an authoritative summary of the key dates, obligations, and how CE marking relates to the EU Cyber Resilience Act (CRA):\n\n### Key Dates\n\n- **Entry into Force:** The CRA entered into force on 10 December 2024.\n- **Reporting Obligations:** From 11 September 2026, mandatory reporting of actively exploited vulnerabilities and severe incidents applies.\n- **Main Obligations Effective:** From 11 December 2027, all main CRA obligations—including conformity assessment and CE marking requirements—apply. From this date, only compliant “products with digital elements” can be placed on the EU market【3:1†source】【3:0†source】【3:2†source】【3:3†source】【3:6†source】.\n\n### Main Obligations\n\nThe CRA impacts manufacturers, importers, and distributors of products with digital elements (PDEs)—essentially, most connected hardware and software. Obligations include:\n\n- **Cybersecurity by Design:** Products must be designed, developed, and produced with safer default configurations and robust cybersecurity throughout their lifecycle.\n- **Vulnerability Handling:** Manufacturers must monitor, manage, and patch vulnerabilities for at least 5 years (unless the expected product lifetime is shorter).\n- **Incident Notification:** Manufacturers must report actively exploited vulnerabilities and incidents within 24 hours to relevant authorities (notably via an ENISA-operated platform).\n- **Documentation:** Maintain up-to-date, machine-readable Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) for each product and release; provide technical files for regulatory inspection.\n- **Conformity Assessment:** Products must undergo either self-assessment or third-party assessment depending on risk category; critical products (e.g., security software, network devices) typically require independent evaluation【3:1†source】【3:2†source】【3:4†source】【3:6†source】.\n- **Ongoing Obligations:** Obligations apply throughout the supply chain—manufacturers, importers, and distributors are all responsible for ensuring compliance and correct documentation.\n- **Penalties:** Up to €15 million or 2.5% of global annual turnover for non-compliance【3:5†source】.\n\n### CE Marking and Its Role\n\n- **CE Marking as Evidence of Compliance:** Under the CRA, CE marking on a product will serve as an official declaration by the manufacturer that the product meets all cybersecurity requirements set out in the regulation.\n- **Precondition for Market Access:** From December 2027, products without CE marking demonstrating CRA compliance cannot be marketed or sold in the EU.\n- **Market Surveillance:** National authorities can audit, require evidence, or order recalls for products that fail to meet the requirements. CE marking is central to both regulatory oversight and consumer assurance of compliant digital products【3:0†source】【3:3†source】【3:5†source】.\n\n### Harmonization and Scope\n\n- The CRA is an EU Regulation (not a Directive), meaning it is directly applicable in all Member States without transposition into national law.\n- The act works in harmony with existing EU laws such as the NIS2 Directive and GDPR, but covers general consumer and business digital products not already regulated (medical devices, vehicles, and certain open-source software are exempt).\n- Most commercial and connected digital products are in scope; pure SaaS/cloud offerings are generally out of scope unless essential to product operation【3:2†source】【3:8†source】.\n\n#### Authoritative References\n\n- European Commission, Official Portal【3:0†source】\n- Deloitte Strategic Compliance Guide【3:1†source】\n- DLA Piper Legal Overview【3:2†source】【3:8†source】\n- Pillsbury Law Alert【3:3†source】\n- Independent EU-focused legal and cybersecurity blogs【3:5†source】\n\n**In summary:** The CRA represents a sweeping shift in how digital products must be designed, maintained, and marketed in the EU. The mandatory CE marking underlines compliance and will be necessary for accessing the EU market after December 2027. Early preparations, particularly inventorying products for compliance and setting up incident response and documentation procedures, are strongly advised【3:1†source】【3:2†source】【3:3†source】【3:5†source】【3:0†source】.",
