{
  "type": "text",
  "text": {
    "value": "Annex VII of the Cyber Resilience Act (CRA) specifies the required contents for the technical documentation that manufacturers must prepare for \"products with digital elements\" to demonstrate compliance with the essential cybersecurity requirements. Here are the key points of what Annex VII demands:\n\n### Required Contents of Technical Documentation (Annex VII)\n\n1. **General Product Description:**\n   - Intended purpose of the product\n   - Versions of software affecting compliance\n   - For hardware, photographs or illustrations showing external features, marking, and internal layout\n   - User information and instructions (as outlined in Annex II)\n\n2. **Design, Development, and Production Details:**\n   - Necessary information on the design, including drawings, system architecture, and descriptions of software component integration\n   - Specifications of vulnerability handling processes, including:\n     - Software Bill of Materials (SBOM)\n     - Coordinated vulnerability disclosure policy\n     - Contact information for reporting vulnerabilities\n     - Technical solutions for secure distribution of updates\n   - Details about the production and monitoring processes and their validation\n\n3. **Cybersecurity Risk Assessment:**\n   - Assessment of cybersecurity risks the product is designed to address\n   - Explanation of how the requirements of Annex I are met\n\n4. **Support Period Considerations:**\n   - Information used to determine the product's support period in line with Article 13(8)\n\n5. **Standards and Specifications:**\n   - List of harmonized standards and cybersecurity schemes applied (fully or partially)\n   - Explanation of alternative solutions if those standards or schemes aren't fully applied\n\n6. **Testing and Verification:**\n   - Test reports verifying the product's and vulnerability handling processes' compliance with essential cybersecurity requirements\n\n### Importance and Practical Use\nAnnex VII ensures transparency and accountability in how products are designed, built, and maintained against cyber risks. Proper, comprehensive technical documentation not only satisfies compliance requirements but also facilitates:\n- Market access across the EU\n- Faster and easier conformity assessments\n- Clearer communications with regulators and customers in case of cyber incidents\n\n### Further Reading\n- The official annex text and complete regulation details can be found on dedicated CRA websites and the Official Journal of the European Union【3:0†Annex VII - Cyber Resilience Act†https://cyber-resilience-act.com/annexes/annex-vii/】【3:2†CRA - Annex VII | StreamLex†https://streamlex.eu/annexes/cra-en-annex-vii/】【3:5†Cyber Resilience Act – Text - Text - SPAC Alliance†https://spac-alliance.org/library/regulations/cra/cyber-resilience-act-text/】【3:6†Read the annexes of the Cyber Resilience Act (EU)†https://www.cyberresilienceact.eu/the-cyber-resilience-act-annex/】【3:8†Annexes - Cyber Resilience Act†https://cyber-resilience-act.com/annexes/】.\n\nIf you need a template or concrete examples for meeting these requirements, there are additional guides available that offer sample documentation and practical tips for manufacturers aiming for CRA compliance【3:3†Cyber Resilience Act Technical Documentation Guide (Annex II \u0026 VII ...†https://goregulus.com/cra-documentation/technical-documentation/】.",
